06267nam a22006975i 9781847425119DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20002000xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781847425119  a(DE-B1597)646637  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 4aHD4645.A5b.W438 2009 7aPOL0280002bisacsh04a352.1422300aWhat works? :bEvidence-based policy and practice in public services /ced. by Huw T.O. Davies, Sandra M. Nutley, Peter C. Smith. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (396 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tEditors’ Preface -- tList of acronyms -- tList of contributors -- tIntroducing evidence-based policy and practice in public services -- tEvidence and the policy process -- tAnalysis by service area -- tHealthcare: evidence to the fore -- tEducation: realising the potential -- tCriminal justice: using evidence to reduce crime -- tSocial care: rhetoric and reality -- tWelfare policy: tendering for evidence -- tHousing: linking theory and practice -- tTransport: beyond predict and provide -- tUrban policy: addressing wicked problems -- tA strategic approach to research and development -- tDebates on the role of experimentation -- tNon-experimental quantitative methods -- tContributions from qualitative research -- tMaking a reality of evidence-based practice -- tLearning from the past, prospects for the future -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat counts is what works - but how can we actually tell what works? And what can we do with such knowledge to influence policy and practice? As all parts of the public sector embrace 'evidence' as a means of providing more effective and efficient public services, this book provides a timely and novel contribution to such debates. The authors consider the role of evidence in specific public policy areas (healthcare, education, criminal justice, social care, welfare, housing, transport and urban renewal), using experts in each field to explore the creation, dissemination and use of evidence within each. They consider in particular: How is research evidence of service effectiveness created? How does such evidence shape policy and influence service delivery? What efforts are being made to encourage greater utilisation of evidence in policy and practice? The rich cross-sectoral accounts of the many and diverse activities in each sector provide an insight into the ebb and flow of evidence as guidance to policy and practice. 'What works?' develops perceptive analyses of outstanding problems, and raises challenging agendas for service development and future research. The authors conclude with the all-important question of the implementation of evidence-based practice and lead the way to the reinvigoration of innovative thinking. With its relevance to both cutting-edge practice and research, this book is important reading for a wide range of managers and professionals in different sectors, as well as students and academics studying public policy, public administration, and social policy and management.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCounty serviceszGreat Britain. 0aMunicipal serviceszGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aAmann, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Huw T.O., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavies, Huw, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoherty, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitz-Gibbon, Carol, econtri